WEBVTT

00:04:16.333 --> 00:04:19.753
NARRATOR: This is a story
of an ordinary little boy...

00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:22.964
...named Charlie Bucket.

00:04:23.632 --> 00:04:28.178
He was not faster or stronger
or more clever than other children.

00:04:30.139 --> 00:04:34.934
His family was not rich
or powerful or well-connected.

00:04:35.102 --> 00:04:38.897
In fact, they barely had enough to eat.

00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:44.360
Charlie Bucket was the luckiest boy
in the entire world.

00:04:44.528 --> 00:04:46.905
He just didn't know it yet.

00:05:03.839 --> 00:05:05.507
-Evening, Buckets.
-Evening.

00:05:05.674 --> 00:05:07.133
CHARLlE:
Hi, Dad.

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:11.471
Soup's almost ready, darling.

00:05:12.056 --> 00:05:15.308
Don't suppose there's anything
extra to put in, love.

00:05:16.101 --> 00:05:18.770
Oh, well. Nothing goes better
with cabbage than cabbage.

00:05:23.317 --> 00:05:24.776
Charlie...

00:05:25.236 --> 00:05:27.695
...l found something l think you'll like.

00:05:30.908 --> 00:05:35.203
NARRATOR: Charlie's father worked
at the local toothpaste factory.

00:05:35.371 --> 00:05:39.415
The hours were long,
and the pay was terrible...

00:05:39.583 --> 00:05:44.420
...yet occasionally,
there were unexpected surprises.

00:05:46.924 --> 00:05:48.424
It's exactly what l need.

00:05:49.677 --> 00:05:51.052
What is it, Charlie?

00:05:57.101 --> 00:05:59.602
Dad found it, just the piece I needed.

00:05:59.770 --> 00:06:02.772
-What piece was it?
-A head for Willy Wonka.

00:06:02.940 --> 00:06:04.190
Well, how wonderful.

00:06:04.358 --> 00:06:06.401
It's quite a likeness.

00:06:06.569 --> 00:06:08.236
CHARLlE: You think so?
-Think so?

00:06:08.404 --> 00:06:09.988
I know so.

00:06:10.155 --> 00:06:13.825
I saw Willy Wonka
with my own two eyes.

00:06:13.993 --> 00:06:16.286
-l used to work for him, you know.
-You did?

00:06:16.453 --> 00:06:17.996
-l did.
-He did.

00:06:18.289 --> 00:06:19.455
He did.

00:06:19.623 --> 00:06:21.624
I love grapes.

00:06:21.959 --> 00:06:26.170
Of course, I was a much
younger man in those days.

00:06:27.464 --> 00:06:32.218
GRANDPA JOE: Willy Wonka began with
a single store on Cherry Street.

00:06:32.428 --> 00:06:35.680
But the whole world wanted his candy.

00:06:39.143 --> 00:06:41.394
-Mr. Wonka.
-Yeah?

00:06:41.562 --> 00:06:43.354
We need more Wonka bars...

00:06:43.522 --> 00:06:47.358
-...and we're out of chocolate birds.
-Birds?

00:06:47.651 --> 00:06:48.985
Birds.

00:06:49.153 --> 00:06:53.197
Well, then we'll need
to make some more. Here.

00:06:55.868 --> 00:06:57.535
Now open.

00:06:58.412 --> 00:06:59.913
[TWEETS]

00:07:00.122 --> 00:07:01.205
[TlTTERS]

00:07:01.665 --> 00:07:03.791
The man was a genius.

00:07:04.293 --> 00:07:08.630
Did you know he invented a new way
of making chocolate ice cream...

00:07:08.797 --> 00:07:12.467
...so that it stays cold for hours
without a freezer?

00:07:12.635 --> 00:07:17.138
You can even leave it lying in the sun
on a hot day, and it won't go runny.

00:07:18.015 --> 00:07:21.184
-But that's impossible.
-But Willy Wonka did it.

00:07:24.229 --> 00:07:25.563
GRANDPA JOE:
Before long...

00:07:25.731 --> 00:07:29.275
...he decided to build
a proper chocolate factory.

00:07:29.443 --> 00:07:32.528
The largest chocolate factory
in history.

00:07:32.696 --> 00:07:35.990
Fifty times as big as any other.

00:07:55.010 --> 00:07:56.678
Grandpa, don't make it gross.

00:07:57.763 --> 00:08:01.557
Tell him about the lndian prince.
He'd like to hear about that.

00:08:02.101 --> 00:08:04.394
You mean, Prince Pondicherry?

00:08:05.062 --> 00:08:09.357
Well, Prince Pondicherry
wrote a letter to Mr. Wonka...

00:08:09.733 --> 00:08:12.235
...and asked him to come
all the way out to India...

00:08:12.695 --> 00:08:17.031
...and build him a colossal palace
entirely out of chocolate.

00:08:17.199 --> 00:08:19.367
[LAUGHS]

00:08:20.244 --> 00:08:21.703
WONKA:
It will have 1 00 rooms...

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:26.499
...and everything will be made
of dark or light chocolate.

00:08:29.545 --> 00:08:32.964
GRANDPA JOE: True to his word,
the bricks were chocolate...

00:08:33.132 --> 00:08:35.883
...and the cement holding
them together was chocolate.

00:08:36.593 --> 00:08:39.929
All the walls and ceilings
were made of chocolate as well.

00:08:41.306 --> 00:08:44.684
So were the carpets
and the pictures and the furniture.

00:08:44.852 --> 00:08:47.770
It is perfect in every way.

00:08:47.938 --> 00:08:51.065
Yeah, but it won't last long.
You better start eating right now.

00:08:51.233 --> 00:08:55.028
Oh, nonsense. I will not eat my palace.

00:08:55.195 --> 00:08:58.531
I intend to live in it.

00:09:01.285 --> 00:09:03.786
But Mr. Wonka was right, of course.

00:09:04.455 --> 00:09:09.625
Soon after this, there came
a very hot day with a boiling sun.

00:09:10.878 --> 00:09:12.879
Mmm.

00:09:19.553 --> 00:09:21.512
[LAUGHS]

00:09:45.829 --> 00:09:50.541
The prince sent an urgent telegram
requesting a new palace...

00:09:50.709 --> 00:09:53.503
...but Willy Wonka was facing
problems of his own.

00:09:55.506 --> 00:10:00.384
All the other chocolate makers, you see,
had grown jealous of Mr. Wonka.

00:10:00.552 --> 00:10:05.348
They began sending in spies
to steal his secret recipes.

00:10:33.168 --> 00:10:37.213
Fickelgruber started making
an ice cream that would never melt.

00:10:37.381 --> 00:10:41.759
Prodnose came out with a chewing gum
that never lost its flavor.

00:10:41.927 --> 00:10:44.720
Then Slugworth
began making candy balloons...

00:10:44.888 --> 00:10:47.890
...that you could blow up
to incredible sizes.

00:10:48.809 --> 00:10:51.018
The thievery got so bad...

00:10:51.186 --> 00:10:53.354
...that one day, without warning...

00:10:53.522 --> 00:10:58.067
...Mr. Wonka told every single one
of his workers to go home.

00:10:58.235 --> 00:11:03.072
He announced that he was closing
his chocolate factory forever.

00:11:03.240 --> 00:11:07.451
I'm closing my chocolate factory
forever.

00:11:07.619 --> 00:11:08.911
I'm sorry.

00:11:25.596 --> 00:11:28.639
But it didn't close forever.
It's open right now.

00:11:28.807 --> 00:11:33.060
Ah, yes, sometimes when grownups say
"forever," they mean "a very long time."

00:11:33.729 --> 00:11:36.939
Such as, "l feel like l've eaten
nothing but cabbage soup forever."

00:11:37.274 --> 00:11:40.776
-Now, Pops.
-The factory did close, Charlie.

00:11:40.944 --> 00:11:44.947
And it seemed like it was
going to be closed forever.

00:11:45.115 --> 00:11:49.785
Then one day we saw smoke
rising from the chimneys.

00:11:49.953 --> 00:11:53.831
-The factory was back in business.
-Did you get your job back?

00:11:54.666 --> 00:11:56.125
No.

00:11:56.293 --> 00:11:58.127
No one did.

00:12:01.590 --> 00:12:03.424
But there must be
people working there.

00:12:03.759 --> 00:12:07.136
Think about it, Charlie.
Have you ever seen a single person...

00:12:07.304 --> 00:12:09.972
...going into that factory
or coming out of it?

00:12:11.433 --> 00:12:14.352
No. The gates are always closed.

00:12:14.519 --> 00:12:16.187
Exactly.

00:12:16.772 --> 00:12:18.856
But then, who's running the machines?

00:12:19.024 --> 00:12:21.984
-Nobody knows, Charlie.
-lt certainly is a mystery.

00:12:22.694 --> 00:12:24.487
Hasn't someone asked Mr. Wonka?

00:12:25.530 --> 00:12:29.200
Nobody sees him anymore.
He never comes out.

00:12:29.993 --> 00:12:34.288
The only thing that comes
out of that place is the candy...

00:12:34.456 --> 00:12:36.999
...already packed and addressed.

00:12:37.626 --> 00:12:42.588
I'd give anything in the world
just to go in one more time...

00:12:42.756 --> 00:12:46.842
...and see what's become
of that amazing factory.

00:12:47.844 --> 00:12:51.389
Well, you won't, because you can't.
No one can.

00:12:51.848 --> 00:12:55.518
It's a mystery,
and it will always be a mystery.

00:12:55.978 --> 00:13:00.481
That little factory of yours, Charlie, is as
close as any of us is ever going to get.

00:13:02.192 --> 00:13:05.861
Come on, Charlie. I think it's time
we let your grandparents get some sleep.

00:13:08.323 --> 00:13:11.117
-Good night, Grandpa George.
-Night, Charlie.

00:13:11.285 --> 00:13:13.369
-Night-night.
MRS. BUCKET: Chair.

00:13:13.537 --> 00:13:15.413
Thank you, dear.

00:13:17.040 --> 00:13:18.833
Night, Grandpa Joe.

00:13:20.711 --> 00:13:22.545
Good night, Grandma Georgina.

00:13:22.713 --> 00:13:25.881
Nothing's impossible, Charlie.

00:13:42.941 --> 00:13:45.359
-Good night.
ALL: Night, Charlie.

00:13:45.527 --> 00:13:47.111
Sleep well.

00:13:57.664 --> 00:13:59.790
NARRATOR:
Indeed, that very night...

00:13:59.958 --> 00:14:03.419
...the impossible
had already been set in motion.

00:15:03.980 --> 00:15:06.107
WONKA'S VOICE:
Dear people of the world...

00:15:06.483 --> 00:15:08.025
...l, Willy Wonka...

00:15:08.402 --> 00:15:12.822
...have decided to allow five children
to visit my factory this year.

00:15:12.989 --> 00:15:16.659
ln addition, one of these children
shall receive a special prize...

00:15:16.827 --> 00:15:20.413
...beyond anything
you could ever imagine.

00:15:20.956 --> 00:15:22.832
Five golden tickets have been hidden...

00:15:22.999 --> 00:15:26.335
...underneath the ordinary wrapping
paper of five ordinary Wonka bars.

00:15:26.711 --> 00:15:28.712
The bars may be anywhere...

00:15:28.880 --> 00:15:34.635
...in any shop, in any street, in any
town, in any country in the world.

00:15:35.637 --> 00:15:37.596
[YELLING AND CHATTERING]

00:16:09.045 --> 00:16:12.590
Wouldn't it be something, Charlie,
to open a bar of candy...

00:16:12.757 --> 00:16:15.176
...and find a golden ticket inside?

00:16:15.510 --> 00:16:20.055
I know, but I only get one bar a year,
for my birthday.

00:16:20.223 --> 00:16:21.891
Well, it's your birthday next week.

00:16:22.476 --> 00:16:25.519
You have as much chance
as anybody does.

00:16:25.687 --> 00:16:28.731
Balderdash. The kids who are
going to find the golden tickets...

00:16:28.899 --> 00:16:31.734
...are the ones who can afford
to buy candy bars every day.

00:16:31.902 --> 00:16:35.821
Our Charlie gets only one a year.
He doesn't have a chance.

00:16:36.156 --> 00:16:38.616
Everyone has a chance, Charlie.

00:16:39.034 --> 00:16:42.745
Mark my words,
the kid who finds the first ticket...

00:16:42.913 --> 00:16:45.289
...will be fat, fat, fat.

00:16:45.957 --> 00:16:47.708
REPORTER 1 : Augustus. This way.

00:16:52.672 --> 00:16:54.632
I am eating the Wonka bar...

00:16:54.799 --> 00:16:58.093
...and l taste something
that is not chocolate...

00:16:59.012 --> 00:17:00.888
...or coconut...

00:17:01.473 --> 00:17:03.766
...or walnut or peanut butter...

00:17:04.267 --> 00:17:06.185
...or nougat...

00:17:06.603 --> 00:17:11.106
...or butter brittle
or caramel or sprinkles.

00:17:12.526 --> 00:17:14.318
So I look...

00:17:15.737 --> 00:17:17.279
...and l find the golden ticket.

00:17:17.447 --> 00:17:19.615
Augustus, how did you celebrate?

00:17:20.283 --> 00:17:22.535
I eat more candy.

00:17:25.789 --> 00:17:28.624
We knew Augustus would find
the golden ticket.

00:17:29.292 --> 00:17:31.544
He eats so many candy bars a day...

00:17:31.711 --> 00:17:35.464
...that it was not possible
for him not to find one.

00:17:35.632 --> 00:17:38.801
REPORTER 2:
Yes, it is good, Augustus.

00:17:39.010 --> 00:17:41.220
REPORTER [ON TV]:
--golden ticket claimed and four more....

00:17:41.429 --> 00:17:42.972
Told you it'd be a porker.

00:17:43.390 --> 00:17:45.266
What a repulsive boy.

00:17:45.684 --> 00:17:47.351
Only four golden tickets left.

00:17:47.561 --> 00:17:52.147
Now that they've found one,
things will really get crazy.

00:17:52.315 --> 00:17:54.316
--of every shape, size and hue.

00:17:58.280 --> 00:18:00.906
REPORTER: Veruca.
Can you spell that for us, please?

00:18:01.074 --> 00:18:04.618
V-E-R-U-C-A. Veruca Salt.

00:18:06.162 --> 00:18:09.957
As soon as little Veruca told me she had
to have one of these golden tickets...

00:18:10.208 --> 00:18:13.210
...l started buying all the Wonka bars
I could lay my hands on.

00:18:13.837 --> 00:18:16.213
Thousands of them.
Hundreds of thousands.

00:18:17.007 --> 00:18:20.801
I'm in the nut business, you see.
So l say to my workers:

00:18:21.386 --> 00:18:24.346
Morning, ladies. From now on,
you can stop shelling peanuts...

00:18:24.514 --> 00:18:27.766
...and start shelling the wrappers
off these chocolate bars instead.

00:18:27.934 --> 00:18:29.602
[ALARM BEEPS]

00:18:42.282 --> 00:18:44.199
MR. SALT: Three days went by,
and we had no luck.

00:18:44.367 --> 00:18:47.911
Oh, it was terrible. My Veruca
got more and more upset each day.

00:18:48.079 --> 00:18:49.538
Where's my golden ticket?

00:18:49.706 --> 00:18:52.041
I want my golden ticket.

00:18:53.460 --> 00:18:57.212
Well, gentlemen, l just hated to see
my little girl feeling unhappy like that.

00:18:57.589 --> 00:19:00.924
I vowed l would keep searching
until I could give her what she wanted.

00:19:02.385 --> 00:19:05.721
And finally, l found her a ticket.

00:19:32.248 --> 00:19:35.542
Daddy, l want another pony.

00:19:37.462 --> 00:19:39.463
She's even worse than the fat boy.

00:19:40.006 --> 00:19:43.592
I don't think that was really fair.
She didn't find the ticket herself.

00:19:43.927 --> 00:19:48.222
Don't worry about it, Charlie.
That man spoils his daughter.

00:19:48.640 --> 00:19:52.309
And no good ever comes
from spoiling a child like that.

00:19:57.732 --> 00:20:01.026
Charlie, Mum and I thought...

00:20:01.194 --> 00:20:04.071
...maybe you wanna open
your birthday present tonight.

00:20:10.578 --> 00:20:11.954
Here you are.

00:20:24.384 --> 00:20:25.968
Maybe I should wait till morning.

00:20:26.219 --> 00:20:27.970
-Like hell.
-Pop.

00:20:28.471 --> 00:20:33.976
All together, we're 381 years old.
We don't wait.

00:20:41.985 --> 00:20:44.695
Now, Charlie,
you mustn't feel too disappointed...

00:20:44.863 --> 00:20:46.822
...you know, if you don't get the....

00:20:46.990 --> 00:20:49.158
Whatever happens,
you'll still have the candy.

00:21:18.688 --> 00:21:20.355
Ah, well.

00:21:20.815 --> 00:21:22.524
That's that.

00:21:24.319 --> 00:21:27.029
-We'll share it.
-Oh, no, Charlie.

00:21:27.197 --> 00:21:28.822
Not your birthday present.

00:21:29.699 --> 00:21:33.035
It's my candy bar,
and l'll do what l want with it.

00:21:39.709 --> 00:21:41.210
Thank you, darling.

00:21:42.170 --> 00:21:43.754
Thank you, Charlie.

00:21:48.218 --> 00:21:49.551
Bless you.

00:22:15.537 --> 00:22:17.663
All right, let's see who found it.

00:22:22.252 --> 00:22:25.587
"The third ticket was found
by Miss Violet Beauregarde."

00:22:25.755 --> 00:22:27.631
Hah! Hah! Hyah!

00:22:27.841 --> 00:22:29.174
[GRUNTlNG]

00:22:43.982 --> 00:22:49.903
These are just some of the 263
trophies and medals my Violet has won.

00:22:50.071 --> 00:22:53.490
I'm a gum chewer mostly, but when
I heard about these ticket things...

00:22:53.658 --> 00:22:55.868
...l laid off the gum,
switched to candy bars.

00:22:56.202 --> 00:22:59.246
She's just a driven young woman.
I don't know where she gets it.

00:23:01.833 --> 00:23:03.959
I'm the Junior World Champion
Gum Chewer.

00:23:04.127 --> 00:23:06.128
This piece of gum
I'm chewing right now...

00:23:06.296 --> 00:23:10.215
...l've been working on for
three months solid. That's a record.

00:23:10.383 --> 00:23:14.803
Of course, I did have my share
of trophies, mostly baton.

00:23:15.221 --> 00:23:19.433
So it says that one kid's gonna get
this special prize, better than all the rest.

00:23:19.976 --> 00:23:23.812
I don't care who those other four are.
That kid, it's gonna be me.

00:23:24.147 --> 00:23:25.439
Tell them why, Violet.

00:23:25.857 --> 00:23:27.190
Because l'm a winner.

00:23:27.734 --> 00:23:29.484
What a beastly girl.

00:23:29.652 --> 00:23:31.778
Despicable.

00:23:31.946 --> 00:23:34.156
You don't know
what we're talking about.

00:23:36.075 --> 00:23:37.826
Dragonflies?

00:23:37.994 --> 00:23:39.661
REPORTER:
But wait, this is just in.

00:23:39.829 --> 00:23:45.334
The fourth golden ticket has been found
by a boy called Mike Teavee.

00:23:47.712 --> 00:23:50.422
[GUNSHOTS]

00:23:57.305 --> 00:24:00.098
All you had to do was track
the manufacturing dates...

00:24:00.266 --> 00:24:03.685
...offset by weather
and the derivative of the Nikkei lndex.

00:24:04.145 --> 00:24:05.979
A retard could figure it out.

00:24:07.190 --> 00:24:09.858
Most of the time
I don't know what he's talking about.

00:24:10.026 --> 00:24:12.945
You know, kids these days,
what with all the technology....

00:24:13.112 --> 00:24:15.364
Die! Die! Die!

00:24:17.158 --> 00:24:19.368
Doesn't seem like
they stay kids very long.

00:24:24.457 --> 00:24:26.875
In the end,
I only had to buy one candy bar.

00:24:27.251 --> 00:24:30.045
-And how did it taste?
-l don't know.

00:24:30.213 --> 00:24:31.588
I hate chocolate.

00:24:31.756 --> 00:24:35.717
It's a good thing you're going to a
chocolate factory, you ungrateful little--

00:24:43.226 --> 00:24:45.060
[MUFFLED DIALOGUE]

00:24:46.062 --> 00:24:49.439
REPORTER: That question is,
who will be the winner of the last gold--?

00:24:55.947 --> 00:24:57.572
-Dad?
-Yes, Charlie?

00:24:57.991 --> 00:24:59.825
Why aren't you at work?

00:25:00.994 --> 00:25:04.871
Oh, well, the toothpaste factory
thought they'd give me a bit of time off.

00:25:05.581 --> 00:25:06.915
Like summer vacation?

00:25:07.625 --> 00:25:09.960
Sure. Something like that.

00:25:13.381 --> 00:25:17.300
NARRATOR:
ln fact, it wasn't like a vacation at all.

00:25:18.344 --> 00:25:22.597
The upswing in candy sales
had led to a rise in cavities...

00:25:22.765 --> 00:25:25.809
...which led to a rise
in toothpaste sales.

00:25:30.481 --> 00:25:34.276
With the extra money,
the factory had decided to modernize...

00:25:34.861 --> 00:25:38.405
...eliminating Mr. Bucket's job.

00:25:43.661 --> 00:25:46.288
We were barely making
ends meet as it was.

00:25:46.456 --> 00:25:48.498
You'll find another job.

00:25:48.666 --> 00:25:52.836
Until then, l'll just-- Well, l'll just
thin down the soup a little more.

00:25:54.297 --> 00:25:58.300
Don't worry, Mr. Bucket,
our luck will change.

00:25:58.634 --> 00:26:00.260
I know it.

00:26:03.973 --> 00:26:05.474
GRANDPA JOE:
Charlie.

00:26:21.824 --> 00:26:23.992
My secret hoard.

00:26:26.996 --> 00:26:30.832
You and I are going to have
one more fling...

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:33.293
...at finding that last ticket.

00:26:34.087 --> 00:26:36.296
You sure you want to spend
your money on that?

00:26:36.464 --> 00:26:39.174
Of course I'm sure. Here.

00:26:40.676 --> 00:26:42.928
Run down to the nearest store...

00:26:43.096 --> 00:26:46.932
...and buy the first
Wonka candy bar you see.

00:26:47.100 --> 00:26:50.644
Bring it straight back,
and we'll open it together.

00:26:59.028 --> 00:27:01.738
Such a good boy, really.

