I was having my semiannual haircut...

01:38:00.160 --> 01:38:03.454
...and l had the strangest revelation.

01:38:17.260 --> 01:38:19.095
WONKA:
In that one silver hair...

01:38:19.262 --> 01:38:21.806
...I saw reflected my life's work...

01:38:21.973 --> 01:38:25.393
...my factory,
my beloved Oompa-Loompas.

01:38:25.560 --> 01:38:28.479
Who would watch over them
after l was gone?

01:38:28.647 --> 01:38:30.439
I realized in that moment:

01:38:30.607 --> 01:38:33.109
I must find a heir.

01:38:34.653 --> 01:38:36.779
And l did, Charlie.

01:38:36.988 --> 01:38:38.322
You.

01:38:40.534 --> 01:38:42.618
That's why you sent out
the golden tickets.

01:38:43.245 --> 01:38:44.286
Uh-huh.

01:38:44.496 --> 01:38:46.330
[WHlSPERS]
What are Oompa-Loompas?

01:38:46.498 --> 01:38:48.499
I invited five children to the factory...

01:38:48.667 --> 01:38:51.502
...and the one who was the least rotten
would be the winner.

01:38:51.837 --> 01:38:53.295
That's you, Charlie.

01:38:53.755 --> 01:38:55.214
So, what do you say?

01:38:55.382 --> 01:38:59.051
Are you ready to leave all this behind
and come live with me at the factory?

01:38:59.219 --> 01:39:00.469
Sure. Of course.

01:39:00.637 --> 01:39:03.305
I mean, it's all right
if my family come too?

01:39:03.515 --> 01:39:05.766
Oh, my dear boy, of course they can't.

01:39:06.601 --> 01:39:08.310
You can't run a chocolate factory...

01:39:08.520 --> 01:39:11.814
...with a family hanging over you
like an old, dead goose. No offense.

01:39:12.023 --> 01:39:13.816
None taken, jerk.

01:39:15.902 --> 01:39:18.404
A chocolatier has to run free and solo.

01:39:18.572 --> 01:39:21.532
He has to follow his dreams.
Gosh darn the consequences.

01:39:23.034 --> 01:39:24.285
Look at me.

01:39:24.453 --> 01:39:27.037
I had no family,
and l'm a giant success.

01:39:28.331 --> 01:39:32.334
So if I go with you to the factory,
I won't ever see my family again?

01:39:32.544 --> 01:39:34.879
Yeah. Consider that a bonus.

01:39:37.549 --> 01:39:38.716
Then l'm not going.

01:39:39.843 --> 01:39:42.052
I wouldn't give up my family
for anything.

01:39:42.888 --> 01:39:44.805
Not for all the chocolate in the world.

01:39:47.350 --> 01:39:49.477
Oh, l see.

01:39:51.354 --> 01:39:53.272
That's weird.

01:39:56.401 --> 01:39:59.069
There's other candy too
besides chocolate.

01:40:00.071 --> 01:40:02.907
I'm sorry, Mr. Wonka.
I'm staying here.

01:40:05.702 --> 01:40:07.411
Wow.

01:40:09.748 --> 01:40:11.582
Well, that's just...

01:40:12.334 --> 01:40:14.293
...unexpected...

01:40:15.879 --> 01:40:17.505
...and weird.

01:40:24.596 --> 01:40:27.264
But l suppose, in that case, I'll just--

01:40:29.684 --> 01:40:30.976
Goodbye, then.

01:40:34.105 --> 01:40:35.606
Sure you won't change your mind?

01:40:38.235 --> 01:40:39.777
I'm sure.

01:40:49.120 --> 01:40:51.121
Okay. Bye.

01:41:12.769 --> 01:41:15.521
Things are going to get much better.

01:41:16.439 --> 01:41:19.191
NARRATOR:
And for once, Grandma Georgina...

01:41:19.359 --> 01:41:22.152
...knew exactly what
she was talking about.

01:41:22.904 --> 01:41:27.283
The next morning, Charlie helped
his parents fix the hole in the roof.

01:41:28.743 --> 01:41:31.787
Grandpa Joe spent the whole day
out of bed.

01:41:31.955 --> 01:41:33.789
He didn't feel tired at all.

01:41:35.667 --> 01:41:39.169
Charlie's father got a better job
at the toothpaste factory...

01:41:39.337 --> 01:41:42.881
...repairing the machine
that had replaced him.

01:41:44.676 --> 01:41:48.012
Things had never been better
for the Bucket family.

01:41:48.346 --> 01:41:51.932
The same could not be said
for Willy Wonka.

01:41:52.100 --> 01:41:54.310
I can't put my finger on it.

01:41:54.769 --> 01:41:57.021
Candy's the only thing
I was ever certain of...

01:41:57.188 --> 01:41:59.648
...and now I'm just not
certain at all.

01:41:59.816 --> 01:42:02.610
I don't know which flavors to make
or which ideas to try.

01:42:02.777 --> 01:42:05.446
I'm second-guessing myself,
which is nuts.

01:42:06.906 --> 01:42:09.992
I've always made whatever candy
I felt like, and I--

01:42:16.291 --> 01:42:18.250
That's just it, isn't it?

01:42:18.418 --> 01:42:22.963
I make the candy l feel like, but now
I feel terrible, so the candy's terrible.

01:42:24.132 --> 01:42:26.717
You're very good.

01:42:38.730 --> 01:42:40.648
MAN: Pity about that chocolate fellow,
Wendell-- Walter.

01:42:42.359 --> 01:42:44.401
-Willy Wonka.
-That's the one.

01:42:45.111 --> 01:42:48.155
Says here in the paper his new candies
aren't selling very well.

01:42:48.740 --> 01:42:52.368
But l suppose maybe he's just
a rotten egg who deserves it.

01:42:52.535 --> 01:42:55.412
-Yep.
-Oh, really?

01:42:55.830 --> 01:42:57.873
You ever met him?

01:42:58.041 --> 01:42:59.667
I did.

01:42:59.834 --> 01:43:04.546
I thought he was great at first,
but then he didn't turn out so nice.

01:43:05.256 --> 01:43:07.174
He also has a funny haircut.

01:43:07.342 --> 01:43:08.676
I do not!

01:43:09.678 --> 01:43:12.554
-Why are you here?
-l don't feel so hot.

01:43:13.014 --> 01:43:15.391
What makes you feel better
when you feel terrible?

01:43:15.767 --> 01:43:17.184
My family.

01:43:17.352 --> 01:43:18.686
Ew.

01:43:20.939 --> 01:43:22.773
What do you have against my family?

01:43:23.525 --> 01:43:26.902
It's not just your family.
It's the whole idea of--

01:43:30.198 --> 01:43:32.241
They tell you what to do,
what not to do...

01:43:32.409 --> 01:43:34.868
...and it's not conducive
to a creative atmosphere.

01:43:35.453 --> 01:43:39.289
Usually they're just trying to protect you
because they love you.

01:43:41.292 --> 01:43:43.836
If you don't believe me,
you should ask.

01:43:44.003 --> 01:43:46.964
Ask who? My father?

01:43:47.382 --> 01:43:49.049
No way.

01:43:50.218 --> 01:43:51.301
At least, not by myself.

01:43:52.804 --> 01:43:54.096
You want me to go with you?

01:43:56.307 --> 01:44:00.602
Hey. Hey, what a good idea. Yeah!

01:44:03.314 --> 01:44:05.649
And you know what?
I've got transport--

01:44:09.529 --> 01:44:12.823
I have to be more careful
where l park this thing.

01:44:43.146 --> 01:44:45.689
I think we've got the wrong house.

01:44:49.360 --> 01:44:50.736
[BUZZER RINGS]

01:45:00.246 --> 01:45:01.705
Do you have an appointment?

01:45:02.248 --> 01:45:04.374
No. But he's overdue.

01:45:07.670 --> 01:45:09.671
Open.

01:45:10.673 --> 01:45:15.594
Now, let's see what the damage is,
shall we?

01:45:56.177 --> 01:45:57.678
Heavens.

01:45:57.846 --> 01:46:01.014
I haven't seen bicuspids
like these since....

01:46:05.061 --> 01:46:06.937
Since....

01:46:16.155 --> 01:46:17.447
Willy?

01:46:19.284 --> 01:46:20.742
Hi, Dad.

01:46:31.754 --> 01:46:34.006
All these years...

01:46:34.757 --> 01:46:36.884
...and you haven't flossed.

01:46:38.970 --> 01:46:40.804
Not once.

01:47:05.997 --> 01:47:07.414
NARRATOR:
It was on this day...

01:47:07.624 --> 01:47:10.125
...that Willy Wonka
repeated his offer to Charlie...

01:47:10.293 --> 01:47:13.045
...who accepted on one condition.

01:47:13.212 --> 01:47:15.505
Sorry we're late.
We were brainstorming.

01:47:15.673 --> 01:47:17.633
Thought l heard thunder.

01:47:17.800 --> 01:47:21.428
-You staying for dinner, Willy?
-Yes, please.

01:47:21.888 --> 01:47:24.014
I'll shuffle the plates.

01:47:32.565 --> 01:47:35.859
You smell like peanuts.

01:47:36.235 --> 01:47:39.613
-l love peanuts.
-Oh, thank you.

01:47:39.781 --> 01:47:41.448
You smell like...

01:47:41.616 --> 01:47:43.450
...old people and soap.

01:47:46.329 --> 01:47:48.038
I like it.

01:47:52.627 --> 01:47:55.128
Elbows off the table, Charlie.

01:47:55.296 --> 01:47:57.673
How do you feel about
little raspberry kites?

01:47:57.840 --> 01:47:59.383
With licorice instead of string.

01:48:00.468 --> 01:48:03.971
-Boys, no business at the dinner table.
-Sorry, Mom.

01:48:04.555 --> 01:48:07.557
I think you're on to something,
though, Charlie.

01:48:19.320 --> 01:48:23.699
NARRATOR: ln the end Charlie Bucket
won a chocolate factory.

01:48:25.076 --> 01:48:29.746
But Willy Wonka got something
even better:

01:48:30.373 --> 01:48:32.874
A family.

01:48:34.210 --> 01:48:38.380
And one thing was absolutely certain:

01:48:38.798 --> 01:48:42.801
Life had never been sweeter.
